{"segments":[{"start":0.4004470109939575,"end":66.7144775390625,"text":"The other thing I learned was something about the art of giving demos: use progressive disclosure, don't show it to them all at once. We used a standard thirty two key I B M function keyboard, used in every computer aided design installation in the world, and all the engineers were perfectly used to it, loved it, had no problems with it. But when we gave demos to people whose business was words, not engineering designs, they would freak out  they couldn't handle all those editing buttons, one of which brought in another overlay of thirty two formatting functions. So I learned very early to make a plastic overlay which I essentially used to cover up all but five of the editing buttons: insert, deeleet, moove, copy and jump. Then we would do an entire demo for half an hour or so with that, let people play, and then we would say, \"But wait, there's more . . . \". And then we would play peek a boo, strip off the first overlay and, lo and behold, there was another row of function keys. And so by doing progressive disclosure with a sequence of increasingly revealing overlays we managed not to swamp and panic people.","words":[{"word":"The","start":0.4004470109939575,"end":0.48053643107414246,"score":0.9989142417907715},{"word":"other","start":0.5406034588813782,"end":0.7208046317100525,"score":0.9669536352157593},{"word":"thing","start":0.7808716893196106,"end":0.9610728621482849,"score":0.999518871307373},{"word":"I","start":1.1012293100357056,"end":1.1212517023086548,"score":0.9998459815979004},{"word":"learned","start":1.2213634252548218,"end":1.441609263420105,"score":0.9973229765892029},{"word":"was","start":1.5216987133026123,"end":1.6218104362487793,"score":0.9862950444221497},{"word":"something","start":1.7018998861312866,"end":2.0222575664520264,"score":0.9936829805374146},{"word":"about","start":2.102346897125244,"end":2.3426151275634766,"score":0.938897967338562},{"word":"the","start":2.38